Introduction¶

I chose this dataset because I find it may answer intersting questions regarding the movies that has high revenues and alot about movies in general, it contain enough features which help answering many questions about movies industry.
Q1) Does higher budget movies mean higher profit ?
Q2) How year time of the releasing date may be related to revenues and profits ?
Q3) Does longer movies correlated to movie profits ?
Q4) Which production companies achieve highest profits
Q5) Which directors have the highest vote rate
Q6) What are the most popular genres ?

Handling missing data¶

1) We can see in the columns left there are few rows like cast, production companies and genres which missing values but only they don't represent even 8% of the data, thus removing them won't affect the data very much, otherwise most of these rows missing data in many columns thus removing them is better

2) The check for missing data above may have been a little bit misleading regarding important numerical columns like budget revnues, budg_adj, and rev_adj because almost half of the rows have zeroes in these columns which may affect our analysis when analyzing the means of this values later, thus we better handle that by replacing these zerores with nans and not drop all these rows.

Functions¶

We have one more issue in 3 columns(df[cast], df[genres], df[production companies] in our dataset that require us to do the analysis in a different way.

1) We have data in these columns in form of lists(groups) which make it hard for us to do the analysis regarding each actor and each genre and each company alone thus we create a function that takes each column alone and return a dictionary with the unique values of that column as keys and and the mean or sum value with the respect of the get_val_col in input for as value

in other words the function just get the sum or avg values of revenues and profits in respect of each single actor, genre, production company

2) The other function plots the visualizations based on input

In [407]:
def lst_elements_calculator( col_name, get_value_col, calculate):
    
    """ This function takes 2 cols as input including a column with many categorical vals
    and return a dataframe of unique values in all that column with sum or avg values for it determined
    input column"""
    
    df_no_nans = df[df[col_name].notnull()]

    #spliting each name val from the col_name
    split_of_cell = [name.split('|') for name in df[df[col_name].notnull()][col_name].values]
    #merging all unique elements from all lists in one big list
    list_all_unique_elements = set(sum(np.array(split_of_cell), []))
    #declaring an empty dictionary
    data = {}
    #This loop iterate over the list which contains all the unique elements, assign each element as a key
    #in the dict and filter the dataframe based on the rows containing that element in the text for col_name
    #and assign the values of the filtered dataframe in get_value_col as the value of the dict key(name)
    for name in list_all_unique_elements:
        #We use try except statement here to avoid an error that happen at 1 row that contain '/'
        #Thus don't excpect that this will cause any data missing
        try:
            data[name] = (df_no_nans[df_no_nans[col_name].str.contains(name)][get_value_col].values)
            
        except:
            data[name] = (df_no_nans[df_no_nans[col_name].str.contains(name[:-1])][get_value_col].values)

        # The calculate argument could be mean or sum if its mean the dictionary value for each key is set
        # to be the mean of values of elements if its sum then it becoms the sum
        try:
            if (calculate == 'mean'):
                data[name] = float(sum(data[name]) / len(data[name]))
            elif (calculate == 'sum'):
                data[name] = float(round(sum(data[name]), 4))
        except ZeroDivisionError:
            pass
    #converting the dict into a df and returning it with the means or sums as a col
    data_df = pd.DataFrame(list(data.items()),columns = [col_name, get_value_col+'_'+ calculate])
    return data_df

Conclusions¶

This data is a sample data so different samples could lead different results
Also The dataset is missing alot of values(more than 50%) in numeric columns probably because most of these values couldn't be retrieved as lot of old and foreign movies wasn't available, so we shouldnt expect some of these results to be soaccurate or unbiased
The non numeric values in the data were not in the best form which required us to extract these values and deal with each one of them in a single manner regarding the populaity,rating, profits meansmost of the data is left skewed which seems natural because normaly only few movies achieved the highst popularity, voting rates, revenues and profits
Even though The data is not sufficient to answer some of our questions but most of these results isn't much far from the reality for example the highst companies achieving profitables in the companies plot are the highst profitable companies in hollywood
Fortunately the popularity and vote columns aren't missing alot of values which hepled as in getting some little accurate results
What we can conclude from our results is that:
1) Movies industry rely most of the time on the budget of the film.
2) Movies achieve higher avg revenues in Summer and spring than in Winter and Autumn with avg of 142 M in summer,125 in spring, 114 in winter and 91 in Autumn.
3) Eon production, Lightstorm entertainment, TFCA , Walt Diseny are the highst companies achieving profits in all time according to this data and Eon production the the highst with a big difference, although that alot of values are missing which means we can't go certain about that but its still not much far from the truth as they ar the oldest production companies and produced the most popular moies in the world.
4) The highst 20 directory regarding avg vote are very close to each other and there is no much difference
5) Adventure, Fantasy and sci fi moies are the most popular from an avg popularity rate of 0.03 to 0.035 in all times while documentary foreign and TV are the least popular.
6) The movies industry is getteing good in the last decades more than before and despite the rise of competency level and even with much higher budget the producers expect higher profits.
